I now have a comprehensive understanding of the codebase. Let me compile the full implementation plan.

---

## Comment Modal Implementation Plan

### Overview

This plan extracts the comment thread logic from `PostDetailScreen.tsx` into shared, reusable components and introduces a `CommentModal` that opens when the user taps the Comment button on a `PostCard` in `HomeFeedScreen` or `ProfileWritingsTab`. The plan avoids adding any new dependencies and uses React Native's built-in `Modal` component.

---

### 1. Files to Create

#### A. `apps/mobile/src/components/Comments/CommentThread.tsx` (New File)

Extract the `CommentThread` component (lines 83-194 of `PostDetailScreen.tsx`) and its associated `CommentThreadProps` type into this standalone file. This is a pure presentational/recursive component that renders a single comment and its nested replies.

**What to extract:**
- The `CommentThreadProps` type (lines 83-95)
- The `CommentThread` function component (lines 97-194)
- The `formatRelativeDate` helper function (lines 47-61) -- used for comment timestamps

**What to include from PostDetailScreen's styles:**
- `commentCard`, `commentHeader`, `commentMeta`, `commentAuthor`, `commentTime`, `commentBody`, `commentActions`, `actionButton`, `actionText`, `repliesContainer`, `commentLoading` (lines 644-701)

**Imports needed:**
- `React`, `View`, `Text`, `Pressable`, `ActivityIndicator`, `StyleSheet` from `react-native`
- `Avatar` from `../Avatar`
- `ReplyIcon` from `../icons`
- `fonts`, `typeScale` from `../../theme/typography`
- `spacing` from `../../theme/spacing`
- `JournalComment` from `../../lib/api/socialApi`
- `Palette` from `../../theme/tokens`

**Exports:**
- `CommentThread` (named export)
- `CommentThreadProps` (named type export)
- `formatRelativeDate` (named export, since it is also used in PostDetailScreen for the post date)

---

#### B. `apps/mobile/src/hooks/useComments.ts` (New File)

Extract the comment-related state management and mutations into a custom hook. This encapsulates all the logic currently spread across `PostDetailScreen` lines 201-339 that relates to comments (state variables, the query, the mutation, reply handling, and toggle-replies logic).

**Hook signature:**
```ts
function useComments(options: {
  postId: string;
  receiverId: string | undefined;
  token: string;
}): {
  // Data
  comments: JournalComment[];
  isLoadingComments: boolean;

  // Reply state
  replyingTo: { id: string; userName: string } | null;
  setReplyingTo: (val: { id: string; userName: string } | null) => void;

  // Input state
  commentInput: string;
  setCommentInput: (val: string) => void;

  // Thread expansion
  expandedReplies: Set<string>;
  fetchedReplies: Record<string, JournalComment[]>;
  loadingReplies: Set<string>;

  // Handlers
  handleReply: (commentId: string, userName: string) => void;
  handleToggleReplies: (commentId: string) => void;
  submitComment: () => void;
  isSubmitting: boolean;
}
```

**What to extract from PostDetailScreen:**
- `commentInput` state (line 201)
- `replyingTo` state (line 204)
- `expandedReplies` state (line 205)
- `fetchedReplies` state (line 206)
- `loadingReplies` state (line 207)
- `handleReply` callback (lines 211-217) -- but without the `scrollViewRef` and `inputRef` focus logic, which will be handled by the consumer via an optional `onReplyActivated` callback parameter
- `handleToggleReplies` callback (lines 219-249)
- `commentsQuery` (lines 256-259)
- `addCommentMutation` (lines 292-339)

**Key design decisions:**
- The hook accepts an optional `onReplyActivated?: () => void` callback so that consumers (PostDetailScreen, CommentModal) can handle focus/scroll behavior themselves after a reply is initiated.
- The hook calls `queryClient.invalidateQueries` for both `['journal-comments', postId]` and `['journal', postId]` on successful comment, same as the current behavior.
- The hook uses the same `socialApi` calls: `getComments`, `getReplies`, `addComment`.

---

#### C. `apps/mobile/src/components/Comments/CommentSection.tsx` (New File)

A composite component that renders the full comment section: the list of top-level comments (each using `CommentThread`), the "Replying to" banner, the `TextInput`, and the "Post" button. This will be used by both `PostDetailScreen` (inline) and `CommentModal`.

**Props:**
```ts
interface CommentSectionProps {
  postId: string;
  receiverId: string | undefined;
  token: string;
  commentCount?: number;
  showTitle?: boolean;        // Whether to render "Comments (N)" header (true in PostDetailScreen, false in modal which has its own header)
  inputRef?: React.RefObject<TextInput>;
  onReplyActivated?: () => void; // Called after reply is set, so consumer can scroll/focus
}
```

**Renders:**
1. Optional "Comments (N)" heading (when `showTitle` is true)
2. Loading indicator while comments fetch
3. "No comments yet" empty state
4. List of top-level `CommentThread` components (filtered by `!c.parent_id`)
5. Reply banner (conditionally visible)
6. TextInput (200 char max, multiline)
7. Post button (using `PrimaryButton`)

This component internally calls `useComments(...)` and wires everything together. It handles `inputRef` forwarding for focus management.

---

#### D. `apps/mobile/src/components/Comments/CommentModal.tsx` (New File)

The main new feature: a slide-up modal for viewing and adding comments.

**Props:**
```ts
interface CommentModalProps {
  visible: boolean;
  postId: string;
  receiverId: string | undefined;
  commentCount?: number;
  onClose: () => void;
}
```

**Structure:**
```
<Modal
  visible={visible}
  animationType="slide"
  presentationStyle="pageSheet"   // iOS 13+ partial sheet
  onRequestClose={onClose}        // Android back button
  transparent={false}
>
  <SafeAreaView>
    {/* Header bar */}
    <View>
      <Text>Comments</Text>
      <Pressable onPress={onClose}>
        <XIcon />
      </Pressable>
    </View>

    {/* Divider */}

    <KeyboardAvoidingView behavior="padding" style={{flex: 1}}>
      <ScrollView ref={scrollViewRef}>
        <CommentSection
          postId={postId}
          receiverId={receiverId}
          token={token}
          commentCount={commentCount}
          showTitle={false}
          inputRef={inputRef}
          onReplyActivated={() => {
            inputRef.current?.focus();
            scrollViewRef.current?.scrollToEnd({animated: true});
          }}
        />
      </ScrollView>
    </KeyboardAvoidingView>
  </SafeAreaView>
</Modal>
```

**Key implementation details:**
- Uses `Modal` from `react-native` with `animationType="slide"` for the slide-up behavior.
- On iOS, `presentationStyle="pageSheet"` gives the native partial-sheet appearance (the screen behind is visible at the top). On Android, it fills the screen but the `slide` animation gives a bottom-sheet feel.
- Uses `KeyboardAvoidingView` to handle the keyboard pushing up the input.
- The modal uses `useAuth()` internally to get the token, and `useTheme()` for colors.
- The header has "Comments" title on the left and an X close button on the right, styled with `typeScale.h3` and the `XIcon` from the existing icons.
- Uses the theme's `bgPrimary` as background, `borderCard` for dividers, matching the existing app surface style.
- The `shadows(colors).modal` preset from `spacing.ts` line 67-77 is available for the header if desired, though `presentationStyle="pageSheet"` already provides a shadow on iOS.

---

#### E. `apps/mobile/src/components/Comments/index.ts` (New File)

